Crime Master Putin
Moscow—German, French, and Swedish medical experts have unanimously stated: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the anti-corruption foundation.
Fortunately, since Navalny survived, the relationship between Russia and Germany does not deteriorate.
In order to demonstrate her "clear position," German Chancellor Merkel announced: Navalny is a "victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can, and must, respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation's results prove that the Russian government is responsible for the incident, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Nevertheless, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is prohibited.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political enemies.
In 2018, former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted, "There is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Narishkin, Director of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even said this was the act of Western intelligence agencies, in an attempt to damage Russia's government's reputation.
Narishkin's claim is clearly baseless, but he also pointed out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
To poison a well-known political opponent just before the upcoming presidential election, and using a poison agent previously developed by the Soviet Union, is simply indefensible.
Moreover, this timing is especially intriguing, particularly as the people of neighboring Belarus are currently protesting against the August elections.
Additionally, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was especially confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If it was indeed the Russian government as Germany claims, this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader (the top rebel figure in the movie "Star Wars") of international politics, interfering in the US election, inciting street protests in France, enticing Brexit in the UK, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, visionary, and cunning.
Then why can't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why can Navalny flee to Germany, and is quickly diagnosed with poisoning?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline to Germany is facing cancellation.
This assassination clearly backfires.
In fact, this further fuels public opposition to the misconduct of the Russian authorities.
Even if it's not Putin who did it, the accusation against Western intelligence agencies is even more excessive.
If these allegations are true, German and Swedish scientists would not have revealed the fact about the nerve agent Novichok.
A more likely scenario is a conspiracy planned by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin wanted Navalny to shut up before the presidential election, or maybe it was due to his anti-corruption investigations.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers are loyal but very stupid; they thought it was a good idea to poison Navalny, and only a few participants knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning attempts on journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the public investigation committee of Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning attempt on Peter Verkhilov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on judicial abuse in Russia.
It can be traced further back to 2006, when Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer, was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
As with the case of Navalny, such poisoning attempts often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was later shot dead in an elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused great damage to the Russian government's image.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to happen. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Narvani's death was the desired outcome for the Kremlin, and pleasing the master Putin is the ultimate goal of the hounds.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning attempt fails, they will not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's interests.
Those who want to find evidence of poisoning may be disappointed.
No matter what, the Kremlin is the real culprit.
The Western countries must clearly state that even if their own economy is affected, they should impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that occur in Russia are attributed to him alone.
